initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In the emerging field of natural language processing, language models have been fine-tuned with transformers to yield unprecedented language skills. Now, quantum language transformers (QLTs) are proposed, harnessing the power of quantum annealing to optimize sentence encoding. QLTs promise faster text classification by reducing word embedding dimensions from n to ⌈log2n⌉. This study compared traditional transformers (TMTs) and QLTs on three popular sentiment analysis datasets, including IMDB film reviews and BBC Sport football articles. Additionally, techniques like sentiment-based text augmentation (SAT-AUG) and attention masks (AM) were applied to both TMTs and QLTs. Surprisingly, results indicated that SAT-AUG and AM did not enhance QLTs' performance. Insights into this disparity shall illuminate our comprehension of quantum-inspired artificial intelligence and inspire further innovations in machine translation and dialogue systems.

In the quest to optimize the interpretation of molecular structures, novel methodologies based on machine learning and density-functional theory have led to unparalleled advances in materials science. Presently, quantum-mechanical solvers are proposed, leveraging the capabilities of quantum computers to accelerate the simulation of materials properties. These quantum solvers (Q-megas) promise improved predictive accuracy for molecular interactions by increasing grid spacing and adaptability to intricate molecular geometries. This investigation compared traditional ab initio calculations (T-AICs) and Q-megas on four benchmark datasets, including benzene ring configurations and polymeric chain formations. Moreover, strategies such as periodic boundary condition modeling and spin density approximation were implemented for both T-AICs and Q-megas. Notably, the results revealed that these refinements did not augment Q-megas' performance. The findings on this phenomenon shall deepen our understanding of computational materials science and inspire innovative leaps in advanced manufacturing and biomimetic engineering.
